Behavior: iterating over strings in JavaScript
- String.prototype[Symbol.iterator] produces an iterator that yields strings for each Unicode code point (not UTF-16 code unit). This iterator decodes surrogate pairs into single yielded string elements representing that code point.
- for (const ch of str) iterates over code points; Array.from(str) and [...str] use the same iterator behaviour.
- String.length returns the number of UTF-16 code units, not code points; therefore length may be greater than the count of iterator items when the string contains astral-plane characters.
Grapheme clusters
- The default string iterator yields code points, not user-perceived grapheme clusters (emoji sequences joined with zero-width joiner, base + combining marks, skin-tone modifiers). Use Intl.Segmenter (segmenter.segment(str)) or third-party libraries to iterate grapheme clusters.
